The paper deals with a problem of Boolean matrix factorization with consecutive ones property, which has applications in graph visualization. This suggests that the paper could belong to the categories of data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), social and information networks (cs.SI), data mining (cs.DM), or machine learning (cs.LG). However, since the paper focuses on algorithmic and optimization aspects of the problem, and proposes new algorithms with theoretical guarantees and experimental evaluations, it is more likely to belong to the categories of data structures, computational geometry, or data mining, which are more algorithmic and theoretical in nature. Among these categories, data structures seems to be the most relevant, as the paper uses pq-trees, a well-known data structure for tree-like structures, to solve a sub-problem efficiently. Computational geometry is also relevant, as the paper discusses graph visualization techniques that involve circular or linear layouts, which are common in computational geometry. Social and information networks and machine learning are less likely, as the paper does not focus on applications in these areas, but rather on the algorithmic and optimization aspects of the problem.
